05674nam a22010455i 9780691214184DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912141847 a10.1515/97806912141842doi  a(DE-B1597)554849  a(OCoLC)1243311920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1998.3.K87bP75 1999 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.430233/0922231 aPrince, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Warrior's Camera :bThe Cinema of Akira Kurosawa - Revised and Expanded Edition /cStephen Prince. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b55 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Viewing Kurosawa -- t2 The Dialectics of Style -- t3 Willpower Can Cure All Human Ailments -- t4 Experiments and Adaptations -- t5 Form and the Modern World -- t6 History and the Period Film -- t7 Years of Transition -- t8 The Final Period -- t9 The Legacy -- tNotes -- tFilms Directed by Akira Kurosawa -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Japanese film director Akira Kurosawa, who died at the age of 88, has been internationally acclaimed as a giant of world cinema. Rashomon, which won both the Venice Film Festival's grand prize and an Academy Award for best foreign-language film, helped ignite Western interest in the Japanese cinema. Seven Samurai and Yojimbo remain enormously popular both in Japan and abroad. In this newly revised and expanded edition of his study of Kurosawa's films, Stephen Prince provides two new chapters that examine Kurosawa's remaining films, placing him in the context of cinema history. Prince also discusses how Kurosawa furnished a template for some well-known Hollywood directors, including Martin Scorsese, Steven Spielberg, and George Lucas. Providing a new and comprehensive look at this master filmmaker, The Warrior's Camera probes the complex visual structure of Kurosawa's work. The book shows how Kurosawa attempted to symbolize on film a course of national development for post-war Japan, and it traces the ways that he tied his social visions to a dynamic system of visual and narrative forms. The author analyzes Kurosawa's entire career and places the films in context by drawing on the director's autobiography--a fascinating work that presents Kurosawa as a Kurosawa character and the story of his life as the kind of spiritual odyssey witnessed so often in his films. After examining the development of Kurosawa's visual style in his early work, The Warrior's Camera explains how he used this style in subsequent films to forge a politically committed model of filmmaking. It then demonstrates how the collapse of Kurosawa's efforts to participate as a filmmaker in the tasks of social reconstruction led to the very different cinematic style evident in his most recent films, works of pessimism that view the world as resistant to change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAmerican Western.  aAshikaga era.  aBakhtin, Mikhail.  aBuddhism.  aChaplin, Charles.  aDersu Uzala.  aDodeskaden.  aDrunken Angel.  aEisenstein, Sergei.  aGodard, Jean-Luc.  aGorky, Maxim.  aHayasaka Fumio.  aHojoki.  aIkiru.  aKagemusha.  aLeone, Sergio.  aMadadayo.  aMarxism.  aNakadai Tatsuya.  aNeo-Confucianism.  aNoh theater.  aOda Nobunaga.  aOguni Hideo.  aPeckinpah, Sam.  aRan.  aRed Beard.  aSengoku period.  aShimura Takashi.  aTakeda Shingen.  aTokugawa period.  ahaiku.  aindividualism.  akarma.  